Y si te cortan el acceso a ...
tu correo, tu bitácora, lo que sea.
Vivir en la 'nube' tiene sus riesgos, sobre todo cuando 'vives en las nubes' y no tomas las precauciones necesarias. En <a href="http://news.cnet.com/Cant-open-your-e-mailbox-Good-luck/2100-1032_3-6246911.html?tag=mncol;txt">Can't open your e-mailbox? Good luck</a> donde cuentan el caso de Tom Lynch: 

<blockquote>
..., a software entrepreneur who lives near Austin, Texas, discovered early last month that he had been locked out of both Gmail accounts he used; he had no idea why. He received boilerplate instructions for recovering his accounts that did not apply to his particular circumstances, which included his failing to maintain a non-Gmail e-mail account as a back-up. He said it took him four weeks, including the use of a business directory and talking with anyone he could find at Google, before he succeeded in having service restored.
</blockquote>

La gente de Google son unos maestros en la gestión de un sitio en el que no hay interacción humana: casi todos los problemas se pueden resolver mediante sistemas automatizados pero .... ¡ay! si necesitas la intervención de una persona humana, entonce puede empezar el dolor.

Llegué a esta historia a través de <a href="http://lifehacker.com/5061023/test-your-web-mails-password-recovery-before-someone-else-does">Test Your Web Mail's Password Recovery (Before Someone Else Does)</a>, donde se habla de otros casos, referenciando a <a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-13554_3-10061939-33.html">Being smart about Web mail</a> que, además, incluye algunos consejos.


